types.name: ID
types.description: The `ID` scalar type represents a unique identifier, often used to refetch an object or as key for a cache. The ID type appears in a JSON response as a String; however, it is not intended to be human-readable. When expected as an input type, any string (such as `"4"`) or integer (such as `4`) input value will be accepted as an ID.

types.name: CircuitType
types.description:
A communications circuit connects two points. Each Circuit belongs to a Provider; Providers may have multiple
circuits. Each circuit is also assigned a CircuitType and a Site, and may optionally be assigned to a particular
ProviderAccount. Circuit port speed and commit rate are measured in Kbps.

types.name: ObjectChangeType
types.description:
Record a change to an object and the user account associated with that change. A change record may optionally
indicate an object related to the one being changed. For example, a change to an interface may also indicate the
parent device. This will ensure changes made to component models appear in the parent model's changelog.

types.name: JSON
types.description: The `JSON` scalar type represents JSON values as specified by [ECMA-404](https://ecma-international.org/wp-content/uploads/ECMA-404_2nd_edition_december_2017.pdf).

preserve historical context around an object, and complements NetBox's built-in change logging. For example, you
might record a new journal entry when a device undergoes maintenance, or when a prefix is expanded.

the hierarchy and track the overall utilization of available address space. Each Aggregate is assigned to a RIR.

types.name: SiteType
types.description:
A Site represents a geographic location within a network; typically a building or campus. The optional facility
field can be used to include an external designation, such as a data center name (e.g. Equinix SV6).

types.name: VLANGroupType
types.description: A VLAN group is an arbitrary collection of VLANs within which VLAN IDs and names must be unique.

types.name: VLANType
types.description:
A VLAN is a distinct layer two forwarding domain identified by a 12-bit integer (1-4094). Each VLAN must be assigned
to a Site, however VLAN IDs need not be unique within a Site. A VLAN may optionally be assigned to a VLANGroup,
within which all VLAN IDs and names but be unique.

Like Prefixes, each VLAN is assigned an operational status and optionally a user-defined Role. A VLAN can have zero
or more Prefixes assigned to it.

types.name: RoleType
types.description:
A Role represents the functional role of a Prefix or VLAN; for example, "Customer," "Infrastructure," or
"Management."

types.name: PrefixType
types.description:
A Prefix represents an IPv4 or IPv6 network, including mask length. Prefixes can optionally be assigned to Sites and
VRFs. A Prefix must be assigned a status and may optionally be assigned a used-define Role. A Prefix can also be
assigned to a VLAN where appropriate.

types.name: VRFType
types.description:
A virtual routing and forwarding (VRF) table represents a discrete layer three forwarding domain (e.g. a routing
table). Prefixes and IPAddresses can optionally be assigned to VRFs. (Prefixes and IPAddresses not assigned to a VRF
are said to exist in the "global" table.)

types.name: InterfaceType
types.description: A network interface within a Device. A physical Interface can connect to exactly one other Interface.

types.name: IPAddressType
types.description:
An IPAddress represents an individual IPv4 or IPv6 address and its mask. The mask length should match what is
configured in the real world. (Typically, only loopback interfaces are configured with /32 or /128 masks.) Like
Prefixes, IPAddresses can optionally be assigned to a VRF. An IPAddress can optionally be assigned to an Interface.
Interfaces can have zero or more IPAddresses assigned to them.

An IPAddress can also optionally point to a NAT inside IP, designating itself as a NAT outside IP. This is useful,
for example, when mapping public addresses to private addresses. When an Interface has been assigned an IPAddress
which has a NAT outside IP, that Interface's Device can use either the inside or outside IP as its primary IP.

types.name: IPAddressFilter
types.description:
An IPAddress represents an individual IPv4 or IPv6 address and its mask. The mask length should match what is
configured in the real world. (Typically, only loopback interfaces are configured with /32 or /128 masks.) Like
Prefixes, IPAddresses can optionally be assigned to a VRF. An IPAddress can optionally be assigned to an Interface.
Interfaces can have zero or more IPAddresses assigned to them.

An IPAddress can also optionally point to a NAT inside IP, designating itself as a NAT outside IP. This is useful,
for example, when mapping public addresses to private addresses. When an Interface has been assigned an IPAddress
which has a NAT outside IP, that Interface's Device can use either the inside or outside IP as its primary IP.

A Service represents a layer-four service (e.g. HTTP or SSH) running on a Device or VirtualMachine. A Service may
optionally be tied to one or more specific IPAddresses belonging to its parent.

types.name: DeviceType
types.description:
A Device represents a piece of physical hardware mounted within a Rack. Each Device is assigned a DeviceType,
DeviceRole, and (optionally) a Platform. Device names are not required, however if one is set it must be unique.

Each Device must be assigned to a site, and optionally to a rack within that site. Associating a device with a
particular rack face or unit is optional (for example, vertically mounted PDUs do not consume rack units).

When a new Device is created, console/power/interface/device bay components are created along with it as dictated
by the component templates assigned to its DeviceType. Components can also be added, modified, or deleted after the
creation of a Device.

types.name: DeviceFilter
types.description:
A Device represents a piece of physical hardware mounted within a Rack. Each Device is assigned a DeviceType,
DeviceRole, and (optionally) a Platform. Device names are not required, however if one is set it must be unique.

Each Device must be assigned to a site, and optionally to a rack within that site. Associating a device with a
particular rack face or unit is optional (for example, vertically mounted PDUs do not consume rack units).

When a new Device is created, console/power/interface/device bay components are created along with it as dictated
by the component templates assigned to its DeviceType. Components can also be added, modified, or deleted after the
creation of a Device.

types.name: PlatformType
types.description:
Platform refers to the software or firmware running on a Device. For example, "Cisco IOS-XR" or "Juniper Junos". A
Platform may optionally be associated with a particular Manufacturer.

types.name: ManufacturerType
types.description: A Manufacturer represents a company which produces hardware devices; for example, Juniper or Dell.

types.name: PlatformFilter
types.description:

types.name: InventoryItemTemplateType
types.description: A template for an InventoryItem to be created for a new parent Device.

types.name: DeviceTypeType
types.description:
A DeviceType represents a particular make (Manufacturer) and model of device. It specifies rack height and depth, as
well as high-level functional role(s).

Each DeviceType can have an arbitrary number of component templates assigned to it, which define console, power, and
interface objects. For example, a Juniper EX4300-48T DeviceType would have:

  * 1 ConsolePortTemplate
  * 2 PowerPortTemplates
  * 48 InterfaceTemplates

When a new Device of this type is created, the appropriate console, power, and interface objects (as defined by the
DeviceType) are automatically created as well.

types.name: FrontPortTemplateType
types.description: Template for a pass-through port on the front of a new Device.

types.name: ModuleTypeType
types.description:
A ModuleType represents a hardware element that can be installed within a device and which houses additional
components; for example, a line card within a chassis-based switch such as the Cisco Catalyst 6500. Like a
DeviceType, each ModuleType can have console, power, interface, and pass-through port templates assigned to it. It
cannot, however house device bays or module bays.

types.name: RegionFilter
types.description:
A region represents a geographic collection of sites. For example, you might create regions representing countries,
states, and/or cities. Regions are recursively nested into a hierarchy: all sites belonging to a child region are
also considered to be members of its parent and ancestor region(s).

types.name: SiteGroupType
types.description:
A site group is an arbitrary grouping of sites. For example, you might have corporate sites and customer sites; and
within corporate sites you might distinguish between offices and data centers. Like regions, site groups can be
nested recursively to form a hierarchy.

types.name: SiteGroupFilter
types.description:
A site group is an arbitrary grouping of sites. For example, you might have corporate sites and customer sites; and
within corporate sites you might distinguish between offices and data centers. Like regions, site groups can be
nested recursively to form a hierarchy.

types.name: CircuitTerminationFilter
types.description: CircuitTermination(id, created, last_updated, custom_field_data, cable, cable_end, mark_connected, circuit, term_side, site, provider_network, port_speed, upstream_speed, xconnect_id, pp_info, description)

types.name: ProviderFilter
types.description:
Each Circuit belongs to a Provider. This is usually a telecommunications company or similar organization. This model
stores information pertinent to the user's relationship with the Provider.

types.name: CircuitFilter
types.description:
A communications circuit connects two points. Each Circuit belongs to a Provider; Providers may have multiple
circuits. Each circuit is also assigned a CircuitType and a Site, and may optionally be assigned to a particular
ProviderAccount. Circuit port speed and commit rate are measured in Kbps.

types.name: CableFilter
types.description: A physical connection between two endpoints.

types.name: WirelessLinkFilter
types.description: A point-to-point connection between two wireless Interfaces.

types.name: ProviderNetworkFilter
types.description:
This represents a provider network which exists outside of NetBox, the details of which are unknown or
unimportant to the user.

types.name: ProviderAccountType
types.description: This is a discrete account within a provider.  Each Circuit belongs to a Provider Account.

types.name: ProviderAccountFilter
types.description: This is a discrete account within a provider.  Each Circuit belongs to a Provider Account.

types.name: CircuitTypeType
types.description:
Circuits can be organized by their functional role. For example, a user might wish to define CircuitTypes named
"Long Haul," "Metro," or "Out-of-Band".

types.name: CircuitTypeFilter
types.description:
Circuits can be organized by their functional role. For example, a user might wish to define CircuitTypes named
"Long Haul," "Metro," or "Out-of-Band".

types.name: DataSourceFilter
types.description: A remote source, such as a git repository, from which DataFiles are synchronized.

types.name: DeviceBayFilter
types.description: An empty space within a Device which can house a child device

types.name: DeviceTypeFilter
types.description:
A DeviceType represents a particular make (Manufacturer) and model of device. It specifies rack height and depth, as
well as high-level functional role(s).

Each DeviceType can have an arbitrary number of component templates assigned to it, which define console, power, and
interface objects. For example, a Juniper EX4300-48T DeviceType would have:

  * 1 ConsolePortTemplate
  * 2 PowerPortTemplates
  * 48 InterfaceTemplates

When a new Device of this type is created, the appropriate console, power, and interface objects (as defined by the
DeviceType) are automatically created as well.

types.name: InventoryItemRoleFilter
types.description: Inventory items may optionally be assigned a functional role.

types.name: ManufacturerFilter
types.description: A Manufacturer represents a company which produces hardware devices; for example, Juniper or Dell.

types.name: ModuleTypeFilter
types.description:
A ModuleType represents a hardware element that can be installed within a device and which houses additional
components; for example, a line card within a chassis-based switch such as the Cisco Catalyst 6500. Like a
DeviceType, each ModuleType can have console, power, interface, and pass-through port templates assigned to it. It
cannot, however house device bays or module bays.

types.name: RackRoleFilter
types.description: Racks can be organized by functional role, similar to Devices.

types.name: VirtualChassisFilter
types.description: A collection of Devices which operate with a shared control plane (e.g. a switch stack).

types.name: ConfigContextType
types.description:
A ConfigContext represents a set of arbitrary data available to any Device or VirtualMachine matching its assigned
qualifiers (region, site, etc.). For example, the data stored in a ConfigContext assigned to site A and tenant B
will be available to a Device in site A assigned to tenant B. Data is stored in JSON format.

types.name: ClusterGroupFilter
types.description: An organizational group of Clusters.

types.name: TenantGroupFilter
types.description: An arbitrary collection of Tenants.

types.name: ClusterTypeFilter
types.description: A type of Cluster.

types.name: ConfigContextFilter
types.description:
A ConfigContext represents a set of arbitrary data available to any Device or VirtualMachine matching its assigned
qualifiers (region, site, etc.). For example, the data stored in a ConfigContext assigned to site A and tenant B
will be available to a Device in site A assigned to tenant B. Data is stored in JSON format.

types.description: ConfigTemplate(id, created, last_updated, data_source, data_file, data_path, auto_sync_enabled, data_synced, name, description, template_code, environment_params)

types.name: CustomFieldChoiceSetType
types.description: Represents a set of choices available for choice and multi-choice custom fields.

types.name: CustomFieldChoiceSetFilter
types.description: Represents a set of choices available for choice and multi-choice custom fields.

types.name: CustomLinkType
types.description:
A custom link to an external representation of a NetBox object. The link text and URL fields accept Jinja2 template
code to be rendered with an object as context.

types.name: CustomLinkFilter
types.description:
A custom link to an external representation of a NetBox object. The link text and URL fields accept Jinja2 template
code to be rendered with an object as context.

types.name: ExportTemplateType
types.description: ExportTemplate(id, created, last_updated, data_source, data_file, data_path, auto_sync_enabled, data_synced, name, description, template_code, mime_type, file_extension, as_attachment)

types.name: ExportTemplateFilter
types.description: ExportTemplate(id, created, last_updated, data_source, data_file, data_path, auto_sync_enabled, data_synced, name, description, template_code, mime_type, file_extension, as_attachment)

types.name: ImageAttachmentFilter
types.description: An uploaded image which is associated with an object.

types.name: SavedFilterType
types.description: A set of predefined keyword parameters that can be reused to filter for specific objects.

types.name: SavedFilterFilter
types.description: A set of predefined keyword parameters that can be reused to filter for specific objects.

types.name: JournalEntryFilter
types.description:
A historical remark concerning an object; collectively, these form an object's journal. The journal is used to
preserve historical context around an object, and complements NetBox's built-in change logging. For example, you
might record a new journal entry when a device undergoes maintenance, or when a prefix is expanded.

types.name: WebhookType
types.description:
A Webhook defines a request that will be sent to a remote application when an object is created, updated, and/or
delete in NetBox. The request will contain a representation of the object, which the remote application can act on.
Each Webhook can be limited to firing only on certain actions or certain object types.

types.name: WebhookFilter
types.description:
A Webhook defines a request that will be sent to a remote application when an object is created, updated, and/or
delete in NetBox. The request will contain a representation of the object, which the remote application can act on.
Each Webhook can be limited to firing only on certain actions or certain object types.

types.name: EventRuleType
types.description:
An EventRule defines an action to be taken automatically in response to a specific set of events, such as when a
specific type of object is created, modified, or deleted. The action to be taken might entail transmitting a
webhook or executing a custom script.

types.name: EventRuleFilter
types.description:
An EventRule defines an action to be taken automatically in response to a specific set of events, such as when a
specific type of object is created, modified, or deleted. The action to be taken might entail transmitting a
webhook or executing a custom script.

types.name: RIRFilter
types.description:
A Regional Internet Registry (RIR) is responsible for the allocation of a large portion of the global IP address
space. This can be an organization like ARIN or RIPE, or a governing standard such as RFC 1918.

types.name: RoleFilter
types.description:
A Role represents the functional role of a Prefix or VLAN; for example, "Customer," "Infrastructure," or
"Management."

types.name: ServiceTemplateType
types.description: A template for a Service to be applied to a device or virtual machine.

types.name: ServiceTemplateFilter
types.description: A template for a Service to be applied to a device or virtual machine.

types.name: FHRPGroupFilter
types.description: A grouping of next hope resolution protocol (FHRP) peers. (For instance, VRRP or HSRP.)

types.name: ContactRoleFilter
types.description: Functional role for a Contact assigned to an object.

types.name: ContactGroupFilter
types.description: An arbitrary collection of Contacts.

types.name: TunnelGroupFilter
types.description:
An administrative grouping of Tunnels. This can be used to correlate peer-to-peer tunnels which form a mesh,
for example.

types.name: WirelessLANGroupFilter
types.description: A nested grouping of WirelessLANs

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByURL`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields`, `interfaces`, and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

enumValues.name: QUERY
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a query operation.

enumValues.name: MUTATION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a mutation operation.

enumValues.name: SUBSCRIPTION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a subscription operation.

enumValues.name: FIELD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment definition.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_SPREAD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment spread.

enumValues.name: INLINE_FRAGMENT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an inline fragment.

enumValues.name: VARIABLE_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a variable definition.

enumValues.name: SCHEMA
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a schema definition.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a scalar definition.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an object type definition.

enumValues.name: FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field definition.

enumValues.name: ARGUMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an argument definition.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an interface definition.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a union definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM_VALUE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum value definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object type definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object field definition.

directives.name: include
directives.description: Directs the executor to include this field or fragment only when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: skip
directives.description: Directs the executor to skip this field or fragment when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: deprecated
directives.description: Marks an element of a GraphQL schema as no longer supported.

args.name: reason
args.description: Explains why this element was deprecated, usually also including a suggestion for how to access supported similar data. Formatted using the Markdown syntax, as specified by [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/).

directives.name: specifiedBy
directives.description: Exposes a URL that specifies the behaviour of this scalar.

args.name: url
args.description: The URL that specifies the behaviour of this scalar.
